    <item>
      <title>Thirukkural Complete in Hindi - तिरुक्कूरळ हिन्दी अनुवाद</title>
      <link>/samskrutyatra/thirukkural-complete-in-hindi/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 21 Apr 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>/samskrutyatra/thirukkural-complete-in-hindi/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;/assets/images/samskrut/Thiruvalluvar.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;तिरुक्कूरळ हिन्दी अनुवाद 
    &lt;div id=&#34;%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B3-%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%A6-%E0%A4%85%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A6&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B3-%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%A6-%E0%A4%85%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A6&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;


&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Thirukkural Complete in Hindi 
    &lt;div id=&#34;thirukkural-complete-in-hindi&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#thirukkural-complete-in-hindi&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are at least 19 translations of the Kural in Hindi. The first translation was probably that of Khenand Rakat, published in 1924. The University of Madras came out with a translation by Sankar Raju Naidu in 1958. Hindi, being India’s official language of communication, it has obviously attracted the most number of translations among all north Indian languages. Surprisingly many of these translations are in verse! One of the last translations to appear is Kural Kavitā Valī, a translation by Ananda Sandhidut which appeared in 2000.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
